commit_message:
Remove configuration usage from executors

Starting with this patch, the executors will not receive any
configuration object, but instead keyword arguments containing possible
options that should be passed down to them.

For compatibility reason, for now, the whole configuration object from
the transport is used, since the latter still uses it.

Blueprint: messaging-decouple-cfg

Change-Id: I9b92b0d98d316ba0be99404d217b5a230e1b3429

commit_message:
Add list of VIF models for vmware to image doc

As of Havana, VMWare can honor the hw_vif_model properly.

This patch adds the list of supported models so it is now
in line with other hypervisors.

Change-Id: I435b4cb440038a0c3e98685d81ac39251c0cf715
Closes-Bug: 1192639

commit_message:
Adds parameter_groups to HOT specification.

The ability to group and order parameters in the template is
currently missing. This patch allows for a new section of the
template, parameter_groups, to be added by the template author
to explicitly define the expected behavior.

Change-Id: I6d8dc4e6490fbfe9cc45f6ca9cb1ac2826e13273
Implements: blueprint parameter-grouping-ordering

Log unsupported source repository types.

If we don't recognise git/tar/etc as source-repositories repotypes, we

hmmm, Ok, so this works for me but breaks offline mode, I'm trying to decide if it matters and I think it does, soure-repositories can now be run (or should be) in offline mode with a previous cache with no net connection. I think this is something we should maintain. Unfortunately doing this would involve a little work in the various places the repositories are cloned, i.e. we would need to test for the existence of a REF and if it didn't exist then go get it (and bring it into a branch)

    sudo git reset --hard ref_$REPOREF || sudo git fetch $REPOLOCATION +$REPOREF:ref_$REPOREF

If others disagree then I'm happy to reverse this to a + review."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-12-19 12:50:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Also, I assume the point of this is so that you can build an image with a source component that is pulled from a pending review in gerrit to test it out?

commit_message:
Improve source-repositories git caching.

We now unconditionally cache the repositories being fetched with
source-repositories.

Additionally, by improving the way we handle repository refs, we are now
able to build images with code taken directly from gerrit reviews.

Change-Id: Ifd4c5691f6761eb5551663e6d0aa1c0e42afced3

commit_message:
Add sleep to search_for function, so that node can be searched

Because Chef server build node index need some time, so when a node is
bootstrapped, it takes some time before it is searchable. So I added a
timeout for Chef building node index.

Closes-bug: 1208201
Change-Id: I55eb383ce98e4765c412ece799f7885e690ab188

commit_message:
Add support for "Not" blueprint priority

Launchpad apparently introduced a new priority called "Not" (distinct
from "Undefined", don't ask me why). This adds support for it.

Fixes bug 1262891

Change-Id: I7d3dbc2078a66571f3806f53aeb058ce4233b75c

commit_message:
Enable packet forwarding with sysctl attribute

Per the Havana install docs this setting is needed for OVS. This will get picked
up by the openstack-common::sysctl recipe which is part of the os-base role.

Change-Id: I7c39ca84dcd0713c2eaebd4b1746342df3f46d96

Add doc on glance property protection

In Havana, glance added a new feature: protection over
the properties on images. This adds a basic document
explaining it to the config reference.

commit_message:
Unlock/Lock can now be user actions

Havana allowed lock & unlock to be performed by
users, in addition to admins. This updates the policy.json
example to be in line with the sample

Change-Id: I6a81d1890173672149293ee41bfa9e553cfb9e04
Closes-Bug: 1206724

commit_message:
Add reference to isolated hosts-iso image restrict

Havana added a new parameter, which is already documented,
that alters the IsolatedHostsSchedule so that IsolatedHosts
can run only Isolated images. This patch adds a sentence
explaining this.

Change-Id: I26d1fe3d3daab4df944f0d9f83e940f953fe1c81
Closes-Bug: 1208526

commit_message:
Add note about windows image timezone

As per the bug report, if you don't set os_type=windows
during upload, bad things happen. This patch adds a note
that says as such.

Change-Id: I0ef2136b4d9e0af56afac62ce5aac8671e03f6cb
Closes-Bug: 1239828

commit_message:
Added steps to upgrade and reboot system after adding OpenStack repos

After adding the OpenStack repos, several distributions need to
upgrade additional packages and sometimes this includes the kernel.
Rebooting also guarantees that all changes will take effect.  I
attempted to cover all distributions with this patch.

Change-Id: I97fbf8f9ce3ff8a403ccbd90f1b0c38d915d9369
Closes-Bug: #1258279

commit_message:
Create volume group when use the LVMISCSIDriver

Create volume group when set volume_driver to
cinder.volume.drivers.lvm.LVMISCSIDriver otherwise we can not create
volume with cinder.

Change-Id: I9d27a19254aa62130c13171d68c0c67e4e3686ce

So mkstemp returns an open fd and a filename. So if you use this method you should use the fd like: 

fd, file_name = tempfile.mkstemp()
os.write(fd, value)
os.close(fd)
os.fsync(fd)
os.rename(temp_file, self.revoked_file_name) 

otherwise use the tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile to use the higher level file interfaces."}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:19:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:26:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Increase timeout for Ambari server setup

The setup might take more then 5 minutes (current limit) if JRE is not
pre-installed on the image and the Internet connection is slow. This
change increases the timeout to half an hour.

Partially fixes bug #1259836

Change-Id: I41279f965c5e7d8c41e1edb800b3e62d38537bb7

I would like to see the test cases updated to verify the new behavior though, rather than just removing the multiple calls case, especially since that's what the bug is about.

Feel free to tldr the rest of this comment since it's just my thoughts on whether the singleton is necessary (IMHO, no).

I was all ready to go on a rant about abuse of the singleton pattern, but thinking about it more I do wonder what would happen if someone (mistakenly) tried to use two different Repository objects to, for example, upgrade a schema.  I'm not concerned about concurrency (I think it's safe to say that calling upgrade on a repository simultaneously in two different threads is a terrible idea regardless of whether there are one or two Repository objects involved), but I am curious what would happen if you did something like:

Repository one = _find_migrate_repo()
Repository two = _find_migrate_repo()
one.upgrade()
two.upgrade()

That said, I don't see any code that actually does anything so silly today and I would consider it a bug if any did, so I think it should be fine to remove the singleton-ness of this call."}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:12:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:15:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-09 17:08:34.000000000', 'message': 'Removal of singleton in migration.

Oslo.db migration.py uses singleton to store defined
`migrate.versioning.repository.Repository` instance containing migration
repository path. Most of plugins have its own migrate repo. Usage of
singleton in point of Repository instances causes implicit and
unexpected behavior therefore as current Repository instance may contain
inappropriate path to migrate repo.
Detected at syncing of Keystone with Oslo.db.

Change-Id: If6187a0f7c4590e1c2cd4d998b25ee90aeac17dc
Closes-Bug: #1259229
'}, {'created': '2013-12-10 10:17:32.000000000', 'message': 'Removal of _REPOSITORY global variable.

Oslo.db migration.py uses global variable to store defined

commit_message:
Removal of _REPOSITORY global variable.

Oslo.db migration.py uses global variable to store defined
`migrate.versioning.repository.Repository` instance containing migration
repository path. At first _find_migrate_repo(repo_path) call the return value
will be stored in a global variable. So all subsequent calls
will return the existing global variable value regardless of repo_path
value passed. This design makes impossible to have multiple migration
repositories in the same project.
Detected at syncing of Keystone with Oslo.db.

Change-Id: If6187a0f7c4590e1c2cd4d998b25ee90aeac17dc
Closes-Bug: #1259229

commit_message:
Clarified example 'my.cnf' under MySQL configuration

Removed invalid lines from example 'my.cnf' and added [mysqld]
section header to clarify location of 'bind-address' directive.
Patch applies to all distributions.

Change-Id: Ieacac9df8162e2d44f7576b858131ec3e7e6f43a
Closes-Bug: #1258276

commit_message:
Remove eventlet tpool from common db.api

There is only one place in oslo.db where we use eventlet - wrapping of
DB API method calls to be executed by tpool threads.
It makes sense to remove this feature from oslo.db code and
use the tpool.Proxy() wrapper in the db.api module in each project.

blueprint oslo-db-lib

POC in Nova - Id7de85dce11f5ea61dfccddf80de7800a2bc4e37

Change-Id: I6fa140f2b1f03c43ae7cab98ac8a12d71188af76

commit_message:
Adds first part of quotas support for Nova V3 API

Adds support and tests for the os-quotas extension
for the Nova V3 API. Note that compared to the V2
version this removes the ability to set quotas
which are not relevant to the V3 API (eg injected
file quotas are not relevant because the
os-personalities extension has been removed)

Partially implements blueprint v3-api

Change-Id: Ifa1c77428424bedf7fb88ef6d7b3843376799d24

commit_message:
Adds availability zone support for Nova V3 API

Adds support and tests for the os-availability-zones
extension for the Nova V3 API. Also implements
sorting for zone host display which was applied
to the v1_1 version, but not the v3 version in
I9ab25ef52d6d19b45a39f04cbcde864ee225b4cc

Partially implements blueprint v3-api

Change-Id: I8daa2503a2dc8767e9157bdfa6c9adaedfc8f3c0

commit_message:
storage: factorize not implemented methods

There's a lot of driver that are not implementing everything, and as
time goes by, this is getting and going to be more and more common. Not
all drivers are suited to do everything, so implementing every methods
as abstract makes a lot of NotImplementedError raising redundant.

This patch makes stop using that and remove a lot of useless copy pasted
code.

Change-Id: I9e48c4f0484033061a3c3461d761e4cea4b8e75e

where we wanted to make sure only the correct information was printed to
the console. However as logging.basicConfig sets up a stream handler on
the root logging object I can't see any purpose to the debug handling in
the actual HTTPClient. Further than this it is completely wrong that a
client library is messing with it's logging level, this should be handled
by an application.

The debug flag is maintained and deprecated in HTTPClient and removed
from the session object. There has been no release since the addition of
session so there is no problem with compatibility.

Change-Id: Ib00f3d93d099ed1a9dd25f17121610a7289f0061
"}]
commit_message:
Remove debug specific handling

I think debug handling was initially done this way for CLI handling
where we wanted to make sure only the correct information was printed to
the console. However as logging.basicConfig sets up a stream handler on
the root logging object I can't see any purpose to the debug handling in
the actual HTTPClient. Further than this it is completely wrong that a
client library is messing with it's logging level, this should be handled
by an application.

The debug flag is maintained and deprecated in HTTPClient and removed
from the session object. There has been no release since the addition of
session so there is no problem with compatibility.

Change-Id: Ib00f3d93d099ed1a9dd25f17121610a7289f0061

commit_message:
Made small improvement for Ubuntu partitioning.

Now user can locate OS partition on any of available
disks on node. But there is still the limitation that
OS volume group MUST be located on one disk. It is
because we do not use LVM for OS partitioning on Ubuntu.

Change-Id: Ieb4f115917722f39ca262c94ed1168d88e7b7a79
Closes-bug: #1261220

commit_message:
Support Django 1.4, 1.5 and 1.6

The default session serializer switched to JSONSerializer in Django-1.6.
Unfortunately, it can't serialize arbitrary objects (such as datetime
instances), there we have to stay with PickleSerializer (compare with
https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.6/topics/http/sessions/#write-your-own-serializer).

Sets Django==1.4 for the py27dj14 tox testenv. Don't relax the version
requirements just yet.

commit_message:
Add ability to get stdout/stderr to sshutils

Added new method `execute_generator` which yields stdout/stderr
data by chunks. Added new arguments `get_stdout` and `get_stderr`
to `execute` method. Now it returns tuple with stdout/stderr strings.

Change-Id: I4b6cf4764981c611679fb90505df8ec197224526

commit_message:
Firstboot script modifications

* Since first-boot.d is already deprecated in DIB proposed
  to remove of its usage from savanna-image-elements
  https://bugs.launchpad.net/diskimage-builder/+bug/1212080
* Use rc.local directly instead of 'first-boot' scripts
* Added chown to ubuntu user for /etc/hadoop dir

NOTE: Such replacemnt is temporary and most likely we need to add os-refresh-config element from
https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-image-elements/tree/master/elements/os-refresh-config as a replacement of first-boot.d

Co-Authored-By: Ivan Berezovskiy <iberezovskiy@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: Ic936be236a0604b1af72cb5553f435cb67f34ece

commit_message:
Fix double DELETE request for floating ips

There is douple delete request for floating ips
deletetion for the same floating ip.
So if ip delete in tests, we do not try to delete
it in TearDown any more

Change-Id: Ifc08be901ddf09e4895c79f5cdc134384331ced9
Closes-Bug: #1262795

commit_message:
Do not try to update records if there are none

On server update, check that there exist corresponding NS records before
trying to update them.

Change-Id: Ied7b26d425b62b7a2d8da64bfde6445d151c4484
Closes-Bug: 1262851

commit_message:
scenario/network_basic_ops: reassociate floating-ip

check that a detached FIP can be associated with a new VM and make sure
it is not associated with the old VM by assigning a different keypair to each
new VM so that ssh connection cannot be made without the right keypair

Change-Id: Ib535aa66638a3e7f2f1549b6e7a21a160377df6a

commit_message:
Convert lvm_mirrors to int

When the location_info is parsed and `lvm_mirrors` extracted, it is not
being converted to int. This causes some boolean checks to return True
even when there are not mirrors enabled because of the u'0'.

Closes-bug: #1258133
(cherry picked from commit 1dff30492f0ce1df3ef01ccc21353248a7207709)

Change-Id: I67c463d9f139fe326bbcab4d193c45459129b514

commit_message:
Put _ ahead of unused variable subdirs

The variable is never used in loop, without `_' before the variable
name, pydev will mark a warning.

Change-Id: I3d63b0729c4ae9ec00ca97893c2ded65595235d1

commit_message:
Comment related to device name in attach volumes

Comment in "Attach Volumes to instances" ("Manage volumes" section), in
order to inform that device name may not match the one proposed by the user.
This limitation is related to hypervisor settings.
The documentation of this issue was recommended by John Griffith in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60257/

backport: havana
Related-Bug: #1217874

Change-Id: Ifa65ec6eecca23e85786b0fd79ae3b8ef8ebd537
(cherry picked from commit 76a040cb59a921142f2af30ef88ad1180fcaf2f8)

commit_message:
Fixed 'openstack-config' commands in compute nova.conf

Corrected section from 'DEFAULT' to 'keystone_authtoken' for the
following keys: auth_host, admin_user, admin_tenant_name,
admin_password

Added commands for the following keys: auth_protocol, auth_port

Change-Id: I31d388958d3756b35081d0d75825138dea2d6a64
Closes-Bug: #1262495

commit_message:
SignalResponder, set resource_id in the correct place

If there is an error creating the ec2 keypair, but we have created
a user, we will lose track of the user id and be unable to delete

Change-Id: Ib8704f1054dd16003849700c659d0fea83c13916
Closes-Bug: #1262177

Corrected link to VMware KB article

Rather than replace the link wholesale, I have restored
that link and added a paragraph that better describes the
need for the procedure described in the second KB article
(Pursuant to Andreas's comment in the review).

Closes-Bug: #1259666

commit_message:
wsgi.Resource exception handling to not log errors

In order to not log some exceptions as errors, the
wsgi.Resource.__call__() was modified.
Instead of check if an exception is a HTTPBadRequest or a HTTPNotFound,
now all the exceptions that are not childs of HTTPError are raised
directly, without logging, translation or disguise.
If the exception is a child of HeatException, then the exception is
tranlated but not logged as an error. When this exception reaches the
Fault Wrapper Middleware it is logged as debug.
Some unused, or only use in test, exceptions were removed.

Change-Id: I105eeb74a55dcabc79cd3926dd88da0e19d1e1f1
Closes-Bug: #1231133

commit_message:
Modified images list to be sorted alphabetically.

Modified the images drop-down list on the Create Instance modal
dialog to be sorted alphabetically so the user can more easily find
their images.

Closes-Bug: #1262376
Change-Id: I9b1757b5bcebec73159bc643f10767537a3f71bd

+ Looks good but why not to add the possibility to set a list of components we want to debug?

debug = True
debug_names = nova, ..."}, {'account_id': 9554, 'date': '2013-12-17 08:25:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

>> + Looks good but why not to add the possibility to set a list of components we want to debug?
>> 
>> debug = True debug_names = nova, ...

Sahid, I agree that it would be more flexible, but I cannot find the case where it would be really useful. The --debug-nova-only option is intended to get *all* the debug messages from nova, but not from third party components and it is not intended to filter debug messages from nova. So I don't think we should make things more complicated. Could you please provide a use-case where --debug_names would be useful and what components could be enumerated there?

As an alternative to your idea is to make debug_names a regular expression instead of list (and name it something like --debug_components_regex), but I think it is not very useful too. So what do you think?"}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2013-12-17 08:36:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This approach is too narrowly directed. I agree with previous speakers. I would like to put the emphasis on the fact that "option has no effect if --debug is on" is the bug which must be fixed but not documented in commit message.'}, {'account_id': 9554, 'date': '2013-12-17 10:52:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

>> This approach is too narrowly directed.

Ilya, thanks for the comment, but the same: please provide a usage example for an extended option to prove your statement. Currently I don't understand why it could be used. Moreover look at the --default_log_levels option. It is close to the suggested feature. Don't think we should duplicate it.


>>  I agree with previous speakers. I would like to put the emphasis on the fact that "option has no effect if --debug is on" is the bug which must be fixed but not documented in commit message.

I don't think it is a bug. There are a lot of options that overrides another ones (e.g. --log_config will overrides a lot of log format options). Don't mind to change it though if you insist so hard.'}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2013-12-17 12:33:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

>>> please provide a usage example for an extended option to prove your statement.

In certain cases you need to debug complicated bug and you don't know where is the cause. You don't need all the logs in the same time. But there is no guarantees that the problem is on the Nova side. Thus you need step by step enabling of extra logging for third part applications.

>>> There are a lot of options that overrides another ones (e.g. --log_config will overrides a lot of log format options). Don't mind to change it though if you insist so hard.

I do not understand why exclusive Nova logging contradicts to debug levels for Nova or any other component. If I have miss something, please describe it to me."}, {'account_id': 9554, 'date': '2013-12-17 13:02:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

>>> Thus you need step by step enabling of extra logging for third part applications.

I don't think the bug in third parties is a common case, but changing a simple bool --debug-nova-only option to a string list one makes its usage more complicated (user should know all the available modules somehow and enumerate them in a list; by the way, how the user should know what components should be listed in --debug_names?). 


>>> I do not understand why exclusive Nova logging contradicts to debug levels for Nova or any other component. If I have miss something, please describe it to me.

--debug-nova-only does not turn on exclusive Nova logging - it just changes logging level to DEBUG as --debug does, but for a couple of modules (nova modules). So --debug-nova-only is just a special case of --debug.


Please also do not forget that it is a bug fix for the bug 1207576 and it satisfies the requirements."}, {'account_id': 7536, 'date': '2013-12-17 14:16:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Yep. Clear for now. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 9554, 'date': '2013-12-19 08:34:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sahid, I am still waiting for your answer to the questions I asked above. Please let me know your opinion. I'll quote them here to make it easy to find:

Question 1 (from the comments above):

>>>> + Looks good but why not to add the possibility to set a list of components we want to debug? 
>>>> 
>>>> debug = True debug_names = nova, ...

>> Sahid, I agree that it would be more flexible, but I cannot find the case where it would be really useful. 
>> The --debug-nova-only option is intended to get *all* the debug messages from nova, but not from third party components 
>> and it is not intended to filter debug messages from nova. So I don't think we should make things more complicated. 
>> Could you please provide a use-case where --debug_names would be useful and what components could be enumerated there?

>> As an alternative to your idea is to make debug_names a regular expression instead of list 
>> (and name it something like --debug_components_regex), but I think it is not very useful too. So what do you think?


Question 2 (from the comments to log.py):

>>>> I think weird we have to disable debug to use debug with nova. A good way is if debug and debug-nova-only, no?

>> I think it is not weird, because --debug is more general, so it just overrides --debug-nova-only. In your case it would be weird why there are no debug messages from nova if --debug-nova-only is specified, but --debug isn't.

Please let me know what do you think."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2013-12-19 16:15:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

sorry for the late, actually I put a comment on log.py but if you think is not the good way we can just wait for the community, this -1 just means my opinion.'}, {'account_id': 7179, 'date': '2013-12-19 21:48:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

log.py in Nova comes from an oslo sync, so this fix will need to be made in olso-incubator and synced to Nova.

https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/blob/master/openstack/common/log.py

I updated the bug with this info for discussion as well."}, {'account_id': 9554, 'date': '2013-12-20 08:25:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Abandoned

Brad, I agree, so I'll prepare another patch for oslo."}]

commit_message:
Add option for enabling debug logs only for nova

A new option --debug-nova-only was introduced to enable debug logs for
nova components, but not for external ones (e.g. ampq). The option has
no effect if --debug is on.

Change-Id: I56e6608b57841820e681155fc043fb36409c142c
Closes-Bug: #1207576

commit_message:
Added "novncproxy_base_url" directive to nova.conf

Added "novncproxy_base_url" directive to nova.conf for RHEL and SUSE.
Also unified formatting/phrasing around this directive and other
directives in this step for all distributions.  Without this
directive, URLs for remote console access to instances reference
localhost (127.0.0.1) rather than the controller node.

Change-Id: Id4e8c09c7bc81a2314bd9fea80e48349f19fb224
Closes-Bug: #1258287
(cherry picked from commit fcb8fec7ec8a5a2feef717c843f4f06491963636)

Add XIV/DS8K volume driver to conf ref

subject: Manually add d2to1 to pypi-mirror element as temp fix
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:06:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-noop http://logs.openstack.org/36/63136/1/check/gate-noop/d1cad54 : SUCCESS in 0s
'}, {'account_id': 8429, 'date': '2013-12-19 15:37:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2013-12-19 20:54:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-12-20 00:57:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I very well may be confused, but I don't think this patch is right :).

If I'm reading that bug correctly, d2to1 needs to get added to the mirror itself.  This change just installs d2to1 onto whatever image you're building.

The point of the pypi-mirror element is to create an image that hosts a pypi mirror that other consumers can pull from.  And, the bug here is that d2to1 is not available in that mirror by default because it's not in any of the global requirements files at https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/requirements/

So, what I think this change needs to do is probably have an os-refresh-config script to run at image boot time that calls out to run-mirror to manually load d2to1 into the mirror."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-20 07:12:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

What James is saying would work as a workaround, but I think - since the pypi-mirror in the undercloud is fixed, and we have docs, we don't need to rush this - lets instead proffer an update to glance to use newer oslo.messaging."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-20 07:12:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-20 08:03:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

thanks James - wasn't sure if this was the right approach - after chat with lifeless on irc i will try and push the fix upstream"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-20 08:03:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Added "novncproxy_base_url" directive to nova.conf

Added "novncproxy_base_url" directive to nova.conf for RHEL and SUSE.
Also unified formatting/phrasing around this directive and other
directives in this step for all distributions.  Without this
directive, URLs for remote console access to instances reference
localhost (127.0.0.1) rather than the controller node.

Change-Id: Id4e8c09c7bc81a2314bd9fea80e48349f19fb224
Closes-Bug: #1258287

commit_message:
Add Savanna client for node group templates

It adds data_processing service with simple Savanna client that currently
supports only CRUD operations with node group templates.

Change-Id: Ic96ae88fcfe164f4953013a2d4433bc9c9bf6c6d

commit_message:
Cannot view detailed image with empty name.

After creating an image with empty name (only space characters in the name),
and attempting to view it, the view crashes.
Glance is not returning the name X-Meta-Header on the response if the
name is not set or empty.

Change-Id: I0c55e302d22552e932bdd32e10d00a103d252429
Closes-Bug: 1261367

So I'm aware of this issue and I've been working to sort it out. I don't think this is the right solution though, by doing this the test-requirements list basically looses all meaning. (and it's already a loosely defined distinction in tempest) I have another patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60611/ to solve this by installing the test-requirements list for every tempest run. Which I feel is a better short term solution, because it preserves what the test-requirements list is supposed to be. It's however blocked by another import error issue which I'm working on tracking down now.

Although, you shouldn't be hitting this bug right now because we don't have any unit tests in tree that currently depend on mock. (It's a blocker for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60379/ though)"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-12-12 01:51:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oh, sorry I misread mox as mock. That is what I get for working on this issue for a couple of days with mock not mox.

I'm curious though where did you see the import error with mox, because we are not seeing this in any of the gate runs now, and I'm wondering why not. The first time I tried importing mock we hit the import failure, so I'm wondering where mox is coming from in the gate jobs."}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2013-12-12 09:56:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Change-Id: I1572d08e9a0b9e79b5f55cd6b2b67904bccabcee

commit_message:
Move mox into requirements.txt

mox is needed for the testr discovery machinery in order to get a list
tests. Without it testr fails while importing the unit tests (even if
they are not being run).

Closes-Bug: #1260094
Change-Id: I1572d08e9a0b9e79b5f55cd6b2b67904bccabcee

Delete stack after testing anyway

Currently test_autoscaling delete stack only if test passed successfully.

Whats new in the updated versions?"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-12-02 09:30:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

With all due respect, what's the point of copy/pasting pep8 and flake8 changelogs in this commit message?

This patch just update the version to follow upstream new releases, nothing more nothing less."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-12-02 15:54:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sure copy and paste may be a little much, but at least point to the changelog. Commit messages should state the why (https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Information_in_commit_messages).  This makes writing up release notes much much easier.

Part of the reason its important to know the changes, is that an internal change in flake8 can break things in non-obvious ways here, and we want to know what new pep8 rules we are now enforcing.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-12-02 16:09:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-12-02 16:10:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
python3: Fix python3.2 installation

While installing pbr with python3.2, it will result
in the falling traceback:

 File "/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/pbr/tests/test_setup.py", line 174
    author_old = u"Foo Foo <email@foo.com>"
                                          ^
SyntaxError: invalid syntax

Change-Id: Iee163ddbe4fbe6a1c4a66b4e329224a74bd9d832
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

'}, {'created': '2013-09-05 08:55:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add glance and cinder request timeout parameter

There is currently no way to change the http timeout for glance or
cinder requests. The default value may not be suitable for some cases so this
commits adds two new config options glance_url_timeout and cinder_url_timeout
that allow the user to manipulate these settings.

Fixes: bug #1207250
DocImpact

Co-authored-by: Takashi Natsume <natsume.takashi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: I5239910a133cdacb90956688296d94eb5735b3e2
'}, {'created': '2013-09-05 11:56:45.000000000', 'message': 'Add glance and cinder request timeout parameter

There is currently no way to change the http timeout for glance or
cinder requests. The default value may not be suitable for some cases so this
commits adds two new config options glance_url_timeout and cinder_url_timeout
that allow the user to manipulate these settings.

Fixes: bug #1207250
DocImpact

commit_message:
Add glance and cinder request timeout parameter

There is currently no way to change the http timeout for glance or
cinder requests. The default value may not be suitable for some cases so this
commits adds two new config options glance_url_timeout and cinder_url_timeout
that allow the user to manipulate these settings.

Fixes: bug #1207250
DocImpact

Co-authored-by: Takashi Natsume <natsume.takashi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Change-Id: I5239910a133cdacb90956688296d94eb5735b3e2

commit_message:
Sends additional headers in API calls

Enabled a feature to send additional headers on API calls.
Currently sending OS distribution in an X-Distribution header.
It relies on an [extra_headers] section in keystone.conf
All the existing headers there will be sent with the format
X-header_title. If some header needs to be ignored, None value
should be set on config file. Ex: Distribution=None

Change-Id: Ice32e78b4a54eb9ea9111c9c1c4763d900de763c
Closes-bug: 1259542

Okay, this looks fine to me, but I'm a little concerned that we lost the explicit test for the infinite loop scenario.  Unless I'm mistaken, a problem with that would present itself as a hung test run, which is nastier to debug than just a failed test.  Would it be possible to add something to verify we're only calling the notification once (say a stub that would fail on the second call?).  The test run will still probably hang, but hopefully the failed test will provide a clue as to what's wrong.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 9349, 'date': '2013-12-10 22:10:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi Ben, you shouldn't have really lost any test. The test that was there specifically tested that once log_notifier was enabled all notifications were disabled, but that's not the behavior we want.  But yes, the infinite loop if it does happen is painful..hard hung my box when I tested it (I wasn't running in a VM), and would be true with the previous test and the proposed tests in the new patches.   

When I put together the patches I did try to think of a good way to do so, but got stumped and wanted to get some reviews in.  Its trivial to test number of times a method is called, but that's not the same as counting time a method was recursed into, so want to think/play with a bit. I can see the value of suggestion, now to see if its reasonably doable. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-12-12 16:28:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Okay, yeah, looking again I see that it isn't quite as simple as I initially thought because you can't completely stub out the recursive call without removing the logic that we're trying to test.  I put together some thoughts on how to do this here (I'm pretty sure Gerrit would have messed up the formatting on my pseudocode, so I put it on p.o.o): http://paste.openstack.org/show/54903/

I'm not looking to do that for every test, just one to verify the behavior would be great.

Let me know if that sounds reasonable.  Thanks."}, {'account_id': 9349, 'date': '2013-12-12 22:48:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Sort of.  I had something like this coded up at one point.   What it doesn't quite allow for is that some amount of recursion is ok.. 

I _think_ this is possible.. sometime along the path after initiating the error/notification chain, a new error is desired to be logged.   That event should be loggable too. The fix as coded should allow that, but the testcase wouldn't allow for it (as it is strictly checking call depth). Yeah, weird.  I saw this in earlier testing - though I never identified the source of the second error log, but runtests doesn't seeem to be working for me today, but I'd want the tests to be resilient enough to tolerate something in the mocked up system doing so.. I could put a depth check of 5 that would still prevent infinite loop, but give a bit of buffer for introducing new unique error logs/notifications along the path.   Heh.. testing this fix has been a whole lot more challenging than actually fixing the bug."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-20 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-12-20 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Allow publish_errors to work with log notifier

Instead of checking whether the log_notifier is configured, move
a check into the log_notifier to see whether the message came from
the PublishError log handler.   This still protects against the
infinite loop, but now allows all of the other notifiers to work.

Removed previously overly conservative check added here,
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/4450/

Tests included to initiate from both log side and notifier side.

Closes-Bug: #1053422
Related-Bug: #883293

Change-Id: I793aa17215b747372f1bf8a6e236e55abd575008

H803 is about commit messages ending in a period. What is the advantage of enforcing this? That does not seem to have much to do with pythonic code :) E125 seems OK, though"}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2013-12-10 16:21:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Jordan OMara

It is always good to keep as less pep8 ignores with the code.
Also, there were not made any changes in code to enable H803.

We already are following H803 in repository.
It is just the switching off of the ignore so that any new code too follows that.

Regards'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2013-12-10 19:10:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm ambivalent. I agree with the principle of keeping the code clean, but the changes here are for rules so trivial that I don't think they affect much.

E125 isn't a bad idea to have in there. I'm more curious why it was added in the first place.

H803 is intriguing. In keystone's tox.ini they have:
# H803  Commit message should not end with a period (do not remove per list discussion)
ignore = H803

I know this isn't keystone, but it sounds like there's quite the story there :)"}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-12-10 20:49:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't think we want to remove ignoring H803.  I believe this is the relevant mailing list discussion:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010837.html

From which the consensus was not to care.

I'm fine to add back E125."}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2013-12-11 03:42:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Fine I would take the point, if we do not want to go with H803.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2013-12-11 03:48:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-11 03:49:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

(For more info - I'm told lots of projects ignore E125 because its so bad)"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-12-11 10:02:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Agree, there's good consensus on ignoring E125 - see https://github.com/jcrocholl/pep8/issues/126 and Iaf782831372ba4e94ea0329675923b822077afa5 and Ic73ab3c4a47f33de9145e0c7db2d8674230c2fe0"}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2013-12-13 03:37:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi 

I can also cite examples to where they do no ignore E125
https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/tox.ini
and
https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/tox.ini

it just separates from mixing of two lines( at logically different levels) into same physical indentation level.

commit_message:
Set "remove rule" field to be required in dialog

The dialog can be open from: the "Firewalls"->"Firewall Policies"
->"More" button of a policy->"Remove Rule"

The "remove rule" field should be required, otherwise, user will
hit error when no rule is select. Removed "required=False",
because it is default to True.

Added 'btn-danger' to the button style

Change-Id: Ifa21419bc93818335057bb16ed2683994c6efee7
Closes-Bug: #1252996

commit_message:
Add debug log for checking used private_key

SSHException(Error reading SSH protocol banner) happens on bug1253896.
In most cases, this exception could happen if a private key (used for
ssh connecting) is different from a public key (stored into a server).
This patch adds debug log for showing the public key is set in a
server, both the private key and the public key of client side.

Change-Id: I4cc387ee2eba0365d05f1e3b20d5f656b53d5242
Related-Bug: #1253896

[{'created': '2013-12-10 05:40:35.000000000', 'message': 'Adds basic servers support for the Nova V3 API

Ports servers support from the v1_1 directory omitting functionality
which is no longer supported directly in the V3 API such as:

- floating ip
- add/remove/list of security groups
- disk config related functionality

Makes the appropriate modifications required for parameter name
changes between the V2 and V3 API

Booting an instance is not yet supported as this will require more
extensive changes as image listing services are no longer proxied
through the Nova V3 API

Partially implements blueprint v3-api

Change-Id: I1116e8d8ebc73176223f4135168cc4ab5d904356

commit_message:
Adds basic servers support for the Nova V3 API

Ports servers support from the v1_1 directory omitting functionality
which is no longer supported directly in the V3 API such as:

- floating ip
- add/remove/list of security groups
- disk config related functionality

Makes the appropriate modifications required for parameter name
changes between the V2 and V3 API

Booting an instance is not yet supported as this will require more
extensive changes as image listing services are no longer proxied
through the Nova V3 API

Partially implements blueprint v3-api

Change-Id: I1116e8d8ebc73176223f4135168cc4ab5d904356

commit_message:
Fix unable to add allow all IPv4/6 security group rule

Previously, if one tried to add a rule to allow all ingress ipv4 neutron
would respond that the rule was already part of the security group.
This happened as the filter for querying existing rules uses a wildcard for
remote_group_id thus returning a false match. This patch addresses
this issue.

Change-Id: I0320013a3869d25fb424995354721929465d2848
Closes-bug: #1252806
(cherry picked from commit 9335ffd7c3eaad0d66d7d19e7760ae12476a5ea2)

(2 inline comments)

The principle here is good, thanks for progressing this (seems I mis-heard last weeks argument as 'never force a module to the start of the pipeline' - I'm cool with 'only force if it has not been configured somewhere else').

But, I'm not sure this yet supports the following logic (as an example):
If gatekeeper is NOT configured, then place it after catch_errors IFF catch_errors is first, otherwise place gatekeeper first. Why should gatekeeper go to n+1 because admin placed catch_errors at n? 

{'name':'gatekeeper', 'afters':['catch_errors']} could cause gatekeeper to be auto-placed after wherever catch_errors is configured.

{'name':'gatekeeper', 'afters':[]} could cause gatekeeper to be auto-placed ahead of a configured catch_errors

What I'm worried about is someone moving catch_errors around the pipeline (for whatever strange reason) causes gatekeeper to move with it, which in turn could cause other middleware to mysteriously stop working as a side-effect.

I wonder if it would be easier to just code the dependency rules rather than try to capture them in a required_filters schema?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-16 18:30:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-12-16 18:48:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
Force catch_errors into pipeline

This commit adds a hook for WSGI applications
(e.g. proxy.server.Application) to modify their WSGI pipelines. This
is currently used by the proxy server to ensure that catch_errors is
present; if it is missing, it is inserted as the first middleware in
the pipeline.

This lets us write new, mandatory middlewares for Swift without
breaking existing deployments on upgrade.

Change-Id: Ibed0f2edb6f80c25be182b3d4544e6a67c5050ad

commit_message:
fix bug(1246551):del immediately after reboot vm
  If the instance was booted again before instance file
deleted, such as rebooted and destroyed at the same time,
if restart has been completed but destroy is still delete
instance file, this may be cause vm is still running but
instance file has been deleted.

Change-Id: I33bca5d32c68b563c58ca345c0860734b3003ba4
Closes-Bug: #1246551

commit_message:
Allow the environment file to be specified via URL

Environment files could be provided only as local files.

Now `--environment-file` option accepts both local files and urls.

Change-Id: I11717275fe3ca18d0849bc34d5bd30879388cb7e
Closes-Bug: #1233914

commit_message:
Add policy check for server's delete in v3 api

This patch add policy check at api layer that follows bp v3-api-policy.
And use 'compute:v3:servers' as the policy scope for v3 servers core api.
Also provide default policy rule 'rule:admin_or_owner' for delete action.

Partial implements bp v3-api-core-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: I5532c0580af6788fd45984b9f8695d777ce8088e

commit_message:
Add policy check for server's start/stop in v3 api

This patch add policy check at api layer that follows bp v3-api-policy.
And use 'compute:v3:servers' as the policy scope for v3 servers core api.
Also provide default policy rule 'rule:admin_or_owner' for start/stop action.

Partial implements bp v3-api-core-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: If32a263dda81c30092e46fe1294e7e78ff68d4a5

commit_message:
Adding ability to relaunch jobs

Adding the ability to relaunch a job from a given job-execution (job configuration is preserved and editable).
There are options to either launch on an existing or a new cluster.

Implements: blueprint job-relaunch

Change-Id: Ibc93beb0ebd0cbb6d6afe0e30ee82c0a43b4f93f

This has been discussed elsewhere. TL;DR: Pecan is probably not fast enough to meet Marconi's needs as a high-throughput data API. We have a graduation requirement bp to do at least a POC Pecan driver to get some real data. To be clear, completely migrating to Pecan was not a graduation requirement imposed by the TC when the project was accepted.

I would be happy to discuss this further in #openstack-marconi.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-12-19 11:06:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I'd like to add to what Kurt said that we're indeed working on the pecan bp. Although, no code has been written yet, we've started to dig into pecan and looking for areas that we could contribute to. [0] CTRL+F Pecan

Also, we talked - several times - with Ryan, Doug and other guys behind Pecan at the summit. We agreed on contributing to Pecan and help with finding areas where it could be improved.

All that being said, blocking new versions of falcon will just hurt Marconi as a project. We also have other graduation requirements to work on and we're doing so in parallel[1].

commit_message:
Allow Falcon versions <0.2.0

Falcon 0.1.7 includes a bug fix wrt accept header parsing, that is needed
by Marconi.

I would like to allow future releases in the 0.1.x series in order to pick
up bug fixes like this without having to update global reqs each time.

Change-Id: I8352e406a1f7b28a53b3aef6c8b9b99f86120d55
Partial-Bug: #1261904

commit_message:
Add wait_for_any method to eventlet utils

This change introduces new utility funtion in eventlet utils, named
wait_for_any. It waits on one or more futures until at least some of
them completes. This is simplified version of concurrent.futures.wait
adapted to work with our green futures.

Change-Id: I2ab50c4e108ea1e9c81f618bd8fa8a8156bb695b

commit_message:
Introduce TaskExecutor

This change introduces new entity in the ActionEngine internals,
TaskExecutor. It's responsibilities are simple: take task and it's
arguments and execute it or revert it when engine says so.

Implements blueprint task-executor
Change-Id: I81c63bf4f43342a630f5aa9872fb14776e481176

commit_message:
Don't assume alarms are returned in insert order

The previous implentation of the tests assure than the db backends
return the alarms into the insert order. This is false for mysql.

The patch rewritte the tests to make it compatible to mysql

Change-Id: I146de0d8cef78b6c734bc6742238b939422645b9

Answered in-line, detailed comments on Line 472 of swift/obj/server.py.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-11 22:20:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

FWIW: This patch on top of this commit works without the int() call in the object server (and gets rid of redundant requests, normalizing the behavior between the two tests):

http://paste.openstack.org/show/51773/'}, {'account_id': 8231, 'date': '2013-11-12 03:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thank you for your comment. The main problem with this issues is some of my (company's) customer complain that the headers: If-Modified-Since and If-Unmodified-Since is not working as they are expected to do when they use the swift as web content server. The If-unmodified-since header is more critical problem because they always fails with 412 error. So I think this issue should be solved one. (with minimizing the side-effects on other functions)
As you comments about the problems, I reported a bug with short descriptions about x-timestamp and these header values. I first tried to change the last-modified header value but that effected on the other codes much. Then I proposed  comparing value with int(x-timestamp) with these headers.

How do you think about applying int() in object-server for the case that if the request is without token? means that request on the public container handle the headers.
Or it is reasonable to apply a conf option to handle the headers with given time-difference tolerance?
Or prevent to overwriting a object within 1 second?
Or how can swift handle these headers correctly?

Anyway, when I checked the object files in the production cluster, there is no object overwriting within 1 second among billions of objects. (this cannot justify the proposed  patch, but I hope you consider this issue at the service level)

Please help me."}, {'account_id': 8231, 'date': '2013-11-12 03:39:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

And I think that modifying the unit test to use the int part of x-timestamp value can pass the test case but cannot pass the real world problem.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-12 04:34:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I see the concern.

The client must be performing a HEAD or GET without the "if-[un]modified-since" headers in order to get a last-modified response header value to use as input to subsequent HEAD or GET requests. Is that correct?

I believe we are caught between a rock and a hard place. The object's last-modified value actually includes sub-second values, but it is not representable via the HTTP protocol. So there is no way to use the HTTP specification to do something reasonable here.

One solution is to change the definition of the last-modified header for Swift HEAD and GET responses so that it is defined to be the ceiling function of the object's timestamp. That would solve the if-unmodified-since 412 response problem, since an object created with timestamp 13.5 would have a "14" in the last-modified header, and a subsequent GET w/ if-unmodified-since: strftime(14) would return the object as is.

The problem with that change is in situations where one object is modified within a second of a previous creation or modification, such that a GET or HEAD in that same timeframe would then return a last-modified that does not reflect that the object has since changed. While this is a "small" timing window, it would be a change of behavior from today and while it might work for your application, some other application would break.

I think the only viable solution is to provide a switch such that when that switch is set to true, Swift will return a non-standard datatime format in last-modified header, and accept that same non-standard format in the if-[un]modified-since headers, where this new format includes the number of microseconds in the timestamp value.

Then a client that does not care about the header formats could simply save the last-modified header as is and use it as input to the others.'}, {'account_id': 8231, 'date': '2013-11-12 06:48:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> The client must be performing a HEAD or GET without the "if-[un]modified-since" headers in order to get a last-modified response header value to use as input to subsequent HEAD or GET requests. Is that correct? 
Correct.

Modifying the HTTP last-modified header format will not work  with many other web browser, http proxy, or web-cache. I tested with a CDN cache server and it truncate the mill/microsecond part of last-modified header and reproduce the problem in my case. And I cannot sure that all browsers customer using allow the HTTP-date with milli/microseconds format in the Last-Modified header.

How do you think about defining a new user metadata for a container that indicate whether to calibrating if-[un]modified-since header? 
And then a user using that container is responsible for taking the risk with overwriting a existing object within a second will not refreshed with GET request with IMS header.
e.g. X-Container-Meta-Calibrate-Ims: On
(The If-Unmodified-Since handler will work with that meta data too.)'}, {'account_id': 8231, 'date': '2013-11-19 02:21:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Rebased'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-19 02:21:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
change the last-modified header value with valid one

the Last-Modified header in Response didn't have a suitable
value - an integer part of object's timestamp.
This leads that the the if-[un]modified-since header with the
value from last-modified is always earlier than timestamp
and results the content is always newer than value of these
conditional headers.
Patched code returns math.ceil() of object's timestamp
in Last-Modified header so the later conditional header works
correctly

Closes-Bug: #1248818
Change-Id: I1ece7d008551bf989da74d23f0ed6307c45c5436

[{'created': '2013-12-13 20:02:59.000000000', 'message': "Remove duplicate debug option from keystone-all

The keystone server was started with the options like

 keystone-all ... -d --debug ...

The -d and --debug options are the same so one of them is
redundant.

This will make it less confusing if someone removes --debug and
thinks that debug is off, but debug is still on because they
didn't notice there was an extra -d.

Change-Id: I1ac977e6b12f1cc44f02b636c1bfb5c115b5b3e4
"}]
commit_message:
Remove duplicate debug option from keystone-all

The keystone server was started with the options like

 keystone-all ... -d --debug ...

The -d and --debug options are the same so one of them is
redundant.

This will make it less confusing if someone removes --debug and
thinks that debug is off, but debug is still on because they
didn't notice there was an extra -d.

Change-Id: I1ac977e6b12f1cc44f02b636c1bfb5c115b5b3e4

commit_message:
Shorten physical resource name to custom limit

The default limit for resources is 255, which is
determined by the column size of the name columns in
other openstack project databases.

The limit for nova servers is 53 characters due to typical default
linux HOST_NAME_MAX of 64, minus the '.novalocal' appended to the name.

The reduced name will consist of the following:
* the first 2 characters of the name
* a hyphen
* the end of the name, truncated on the left to bring
  the name length within the limit

The validation fix from bug: #1238272 has been removed.
Closes-Bug: #1250291

(cherry picked from commit 574f3ea54b1299f7f827bf0f6a88a83bccf9c3af)

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/resources/server.py

Change-Id: Iccaf905b2e73433a671559c49223c2b635402853

commit_message:
Correct env variable in file oslo.config.generator.rc

Use CEILOMETER_CONFIG_GENERATOR_EXTRA_MODULES as the environment
variable to include keystoneclient middleware's option in the config
generator's output.

Change-Id: Ibddeb587b22a0569dcb8db58d7cd8626b4482cb6
Closes-Bug: 1262331

commit_message:
Allow running of proxy and storage on the same node.

This adds conditionals to support a installation
in which a user desires to run both swift proxy and
storage on the same node.

Change-Id: I0cc827525968a9d1dc836c553a39f0ac13c4667e

commit_message:
Replace xrange in for loop with range

xrange is not supported in python 3, so replace it with six.moves.range

Change-Id: I9356d176d2c848880fbc6e94509b4fee91a68481
Closes-Bug: #1261984

The failure appears to be bug 1253896

This means we need to be careful about this patch not introducing behaviour which might trigger the issue:

- possible causes are one of the following events not happening before the tiemout:
   * Floating IP not wired (unlikely to be made worse by this patch)
   * VM port or Router internal port not wired (possibly affected by this patch)
   * DHCP address not assigned to instance (unlikely to be affected by this patch)

Before triggering a reverify, please wait for the author to confirm the above conditions do not happen. If they happen instead, the author will provide a reasonable explanation or put the patch in WIP.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-12-16 21:15:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: No score

I have analysed the logs and the root cause appears to be that the VM never sends a DHCPDISCOVER message. Or at least that message is never received.

The dnsmasq process is up and running, and the host being launched is correctly configured in the hosts file (the DHCPRELEASE message is indeed sent on teardown).
All the logical ports are wired long before the timeout, as well as floating IP.

I therefore would vote for a reverify on this patch as I am not able to link it to the failure. It would if there were an issue stemming from a notification not being sent where it should instead be, but it does not seem the case.

Anyway, it's up to another core reviewer making the call."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-12-17 00:55:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Do not trigger agent notification if bindings do not change

The method _process_port_bindings for the ml2 plugin should not
return True when the host binding does not change, otherwise an
unnecessary notification will be sent to the agent

Closes-Bug: #1255680
Related-Bug: #1253896
Partially Implements: neutron-tempest-parallel

Change-Id: I8a40090af347ca430ff6c8e2211fa34bb2bd0f8c

commit_message:
Change Oslo log imports to be consistent

In service.py, Oslo log was imported as "log" and in other Solum files Oslo
log is imported "as logging".  Changed service.py to be consistent with the
rest of the code for easier searching and code consistency.

Change-Id: I239248452466af6343a08d35f704b1925c090cd5

commit_message:
Fix broken HEAT_FETCHED_TEST_IMAGE

The value should not have .qcow2 appended to the end.

This prevents heat-slow tests from running in experimental.

Change-Id: If42d421942e4371d11019079933f67687196362a

commit_message:
Add unit tests for rest_client

This commit adds the first unit tests for the rest client. This is just
the first basic set of tests which were written to mostly verify some
common fake objects that will be useful moving forward. The intent is
for more advanced to be built off of this.

Partially implements bp unit-tests

Change-Id: I19173523ceec3c4fce62f9a3ab61cc9ee23c1801

commit_message:
Remove start index 0 in range()

Remove the useless arg ("start index" = 0) in files, since its default
value is 0, to make code cleaner.

Fixes bug #1259560

Change-Id: Id595630f97b21cc84aefc39b31e7f09f5fb8deb9

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary spaces from messages

If a timeout happens in _status_timeout(), exception message includes
many spaces like the following:

Timed out waiting for thing <<id>>                       to become ..

This patch removes them for log readability.

Change-Id: I5cfea5b447bcdd280b25878e95fa938229038d25

commit_message:
port instance_usage_audit tests into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I7d1e6437cca25ab7da4e1d74f617e51f17951ba6

commit_message:
WSDL patch script for vmware drivers

SOAP SUDS drivers may benefit from local storage and repair of WSDL files.
Support classes add hooks for WSDL "repair" actions.

This patch contains a simple script for the purpose of manually downloading
and patching WSDL files for use with SUDS.

Change-Id: Ib43901535041f32bfea01235be0ddbe52baca548
Blueprint: autowsdl-caching

commit_message:
Refactor cross_tenant_connectivity for tenant isolation

Closes-Bug: #1262613

Fetch tenant creds from isolated_creds if needed to allow for parallel
execution

Change-Id: I507899fd0b4a0bec3312bfb394363d9591b38282

commit_message:
Replace DEVSTACK_GATE_ZEROMQ for DEVSTACK_GATE_MQ_DRIVER

Patch 2/2 this remove permanently the var DEVSTACK_GATE_ZEROMQ
It's necessary update jenkins job builder to reflect this change
otherwise, it will fail.
Depends on change 59995.

Change-Id: Id4c280ecbb0320c5218e8018461637aa67bf47f6

'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-12-10 06:17:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

please put something in the doc tree telling me how to use (test) this - I'd
recommend overview_auth - see specifically the link to
swift.common.middleware.acl which describes the format of X-Container-Read and X-Container-Write.

This change needs a DocImpact tag in the commit message:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/DocImpact

The container ACL's have some pretty boss functional tests in
test/functionalnosetests - grep for use_account - I'd be really keen on seeing something like that for account ACL's before they come in so we're not setting up the next poor sap that comes along accidentally introducing a massive security bug cause we merged them without functional tests validating these things actually continue to work as expected around corner cases.

also, request_helpers seems like a weird place to extend acl parsing - why not
swift.common.middleware.acl

Please reconsider the cost of adding an new format for ACL's into a long lived stable v1.0 API like Swift's.  I really think the simplest thing that would work has *got* to be just X-Account-Read/Write/Admin with a list of comma separated values AND it'd be consistent with what came before it.

I'm sure there's *some* value with a "VERSION" attribute even when you are just trying to represent *literally the* most primitive possible data "structure" (a list of values of a single type) and that some people would probably argue that offsets all the pain of balancing {'s when working with the API from curl (or troubleshooting a customer's invalid ACL with them over the phone) - but I don't think I can overstate my embarrassment if every client author who's going to be wondering why they can't reuse their acl methods between accounts and containers rolls their eyes at those silly swift developers as they type out "acl_list" - since the level of access is included in the header value rather than the list would it make more sense to call it just "members".  /me secretly dreams he might actually get the simplest thing that would work with-out having to fork the patch and sell his soul for +2's'}, {'account_id': 8262, 'date': '2013-12-10 18:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Clay and Darrell -- It feels to me like you two are pointing me in opposite directions, so I'm going to wait for you two to fight it out amongst yourselves. :)  I'm fine with either of the following models:

(1) Auth systems are largely independent of each other, though they can be explicitly designed to play nice together.  So there's nothing wrong with implementing the simplest option in TempAuth -- if a different auth system needs something fancy, they'll implement it, and there's no need to worry about it playing nice with TempAuth (e.g. pre-existing ACL values failing parsing and causing exceptions).  And there's no need to design a heavyweight robust ACL syntax, because as soon as anyone needs a Version 2, they'll just build a new auth system.  And by convention, people won't run incompatible auth systems together in a single Swift installation.

(2) Auth systems should largely be compatible with each other, following the lead of the reference implementation TempAuth, unless there's a specific need for a specific auth system to strike out on its own.  It should be possible, without much special effort, to have multiple auth systems running together in the same Swift installation.  So the syntax of ACLs needs to be robust and general enough to support not only a basic reference implementation (today's TempAuth), but ACLs for other auth systems (some of which we can't imagine today) which might have different structures, e.g. something more complex than a "members" list.  Backward- and forward-compatibility is obviously required.

I had implemented (1) in patchset 9, but Darrell convinced me to prefer (2).  Now Clay is voting against (2).  I'm fine with either.  Let me know what you two decide on.

Clay, regarding request_helpers.py: If we go with (1), I think that the functions should go in the TempAuth module, to emphasize that each auth system makes its own choices about ACL format, serialization, etc.  If we go with (2), I'm fine putting the functions in request_helpers, common.middleware.acl, or anywhere else -- I just need agreement between you and Darrell.

Already changed, patchset pending: "acl_list" changed to "members" everywhere including function names and tests; documentation written in doc tree and added to TempAuth class comments.

Meanwhile, I'll read up on DocImpact and see if I can make functional tests work on my machine with any confidence...'}, {'account_id': 8262, 'date': '2013-12-11 00:17:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-11 00:54:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Doesn't seem to work

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-25 22:43:58.000000000', 'message': 'Implement account ACLs in tempauth, using the X-Account-Acl-* headers

Accounts now have three headers that represent ACLs, so that auth systems
can easily represent general account access (as opposed to container-level
access).  These headers are X-Account-Acl-Read-Only, X-Account-Acl-Read-Write,
and X-Account-Acl-Admin.

Swift requires swift_owner access to set or view those headers, but puts no
conditions or expectations on their content.  Auth systems (including
tempauth) are responsible for defining the content of those headers and
taking action based on them.

This patch defines the format of the headers (in the header_to_acl_list
method and its counterpart, acl_list_to_header), and teaches tempauth to
take action based on them.  Tempauth now sets swift_owner=True if the user
is on the Admin ACL, authorizes GET/HEAD/OPTIONS requests if the user is on
any ACL, authorizes PUT/POST/DELETE requests if the user is on the admin or
read-write ACL, etc.

Core Swift is responsible for stripping out the (privileged) ACL headers
from GET responses if the user is not a swift_owner.

Change-Id: I974865ce79327d6ae4a3955b125d603914a7b936

commit_message:
Implement account ACLs in tempauth, using the X-Account-Acl-* headers

Accounts now have three headers that represent ACLs, so that auth systems
can easily represent general account access (as opposed to container-level
access).  These headers are X-Account-Acl-Read-Only, X-Account-Acl-Read-Write,
and X-Account-Acl-Admin.

Swift requires swift_owner access to set or view those headers, but puts no
conditions or expectations on their content.  Auth systems (including
tempauth) are responsible for defining the content of those headers and
taking action based on them.

This patch defines the format of the headers (in the header_to_acl_list
method and its counterpart, acl_list_to_header), and teaches tempauth to
take action based on them.  Tempauth now sets swift_owner=True if the user
is on the Admin ACL, authorizes GET/HEAD/OPTIONS requests if the user is on
any ACL, authorizes PUT/POST/DELETE requests if the user is on the admin or
read-write ACL, etc.

Core Swift is responsible for stripping out the (privileged) ACL headers
from GET responses if the user is not a swift_owner.

DocImpact: Documentation for the new ACL usage and format appears in
summary form in doc/source/overview_auth.rst, and in more detail in
swift/common/middleware/tempauth.py in the TempAuth class docstring.
I leave it to the Swift doc team to determine whether more is needed.

Change-Id: I974865ce79327d6ae4a3955b125d603914a7b936

access).  These headers are X-Account-Acl-Read-Only, X-Account-Acl-Read-Write,
and X-Account-Acl-Admin.

This patch handles the task of restricting read and write authorization on
these sensitive headers, requiring swift_owner to be True in order to read
or write them.  However, from this patch's (and core Swift's) perspective,
these headers are opaque strings.  The interpretation of the headers is
the responsibility the auth system, which will both define the format and
take action based on the content.

Read-only access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this
list of identities can read everything (except privileged headers) in
the account.  Specifically, a user with read-only account access can get
a list of containers in the account, list the contents of any container,
retrieve any object, and see the (non-privileged) headers of the
account, any container, or any object.

Read-write access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this
list of identities can read or write (or create) any container.  A user
with read-write account access can create new containers, set any
unprivileged container headers, overwrite objects, delete containers,
etc.  A read-write user can NOT set account headers (or perform any
PUT/POST/DELETE requests on the account).

Admin access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this list of
identities has "swift_owner" privileges.  A user with admin account access
can do anything the account owner can, including setting account headers
and any privileged headers -- and thus granting read-only, read-write, or
admin access to other users.

The auth system is responsible for making decisions based on these headers,
if it chooses to support their use.  Therefore the above access level
descriptions are necessarily advisory only.

commit_message:
Persist and restrict access to account ACL headers

(X-Account-Acl-Read-Only, X-Account-Acl-Read-Write, X-Account-Acl-Admin)

Accounts now have three headers that represent ACLs, so that auth systems
can easily represent general account access (as opposed to container-level
access).  These headers are X-Account-Acl-Read-Only, X-Account-Acl-Read-Write,
and X-Account-Acl-Admin.

This patch handles the task of restricting read and write authorization on
these sensitive headers, requiring swift_owner to be True in order to read
or write them.  However, from this patch's (and core Swift's) perspective,
these headers are opaque strings.  The interpretation of the headers is
the responsibility the auth system, which will both define the format and
take action based on the content.

Read-only access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this
list of identities can read everything (except privileged headers) in
the account.  Specifically, a user with read-only account access can get
a list of containers in the account, list the contents of any container,
retrieve any object, and see the (non-privileged) headers of the
account, any container, or any object.

Read-write access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this
list of identities can read or write (or create) any container.  A user
with read-write account access can create new containers, set any
unprivileged container headers, overwrite objects, delete containers,
etc.  A read-write user can NOT set account headers (or perform any
PUT/POST/DELETE requests on the account).

Admin access is intended to indicate to the auth system that this list of
identities has "swift_owner" privileges.  A user with admin account access
can do anything the account owner can, including setting account headers
and any privileged headers -- and thus granting read-only, read-write, or
admin access to other users.

The auth system is responsible for making decisions based on these headers,
if it chooses to support their use.  Therefore the above access level
descriptions are necessarily advisory only.

Change-Id: If10d3941082a22652cf5ab2a511507f62ec0b8b9

commit_message:
Only initialize the glance_http if service is enabled

This commit just adds a check to see if glance is set as enabled in
the config file before initializing the glance http client. Previously
regardless of whether glance was enabled or not glance_http would
auth against keystone.

Closes-Bug: #1214774
Change-Id: I07127c21d55d58fdb294468a0b74ce2bc54d8719

commit_message:
WIP: Convert v3 images code to target Glance

This is part of a chain of commits that I was working on for
the v3 api.  I'm no longer going to have time to finish that
work, so I'm pushing my changes thus far in case they would be
useful to someone else.

Some of the images functionality is still needed by other
novaclient operations, so allow it to continue working without
the removed v3 Nova extension.

bp v3-api

Change-Id: Ia4b3c18bf13aefbe6befbe97916c63110d364cb8

commit_message:
Fix copy/paste errors in API docstrings

Fix some inappropriate docstring, like:

1. "Gets detailed information for a stack" as the docstring for show() in
   events.py
2. "Lists summary information for all resources" as the docstring for
   index() in events.py
3. "Gets detailed information for a stack" as the docstring for show() in
   resources.py
4. "Gets detailed information for a stack " as the docstring for
   metadata() in resources.py

Change-Id: I38fc6a18224d1537bf6981ba60bffc31768b7443
Closes-Bug: #1261615

commit_message:
Sync base and exceptions from oslo

In the process of unification of the clients code we should
reuse common functionality from Oslo.

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2

Change-Id: Ic19d3eb47b94acec4ed86e95b04ffe7cca0792dc

commit_message:
Fixed 'openstack-config' commands in controller nova.conf

Corrected section from 'DEFAULT' to 'keystone_authtoken' for the
following keys: auth_host, admin_user, admin_tenant_name,
admin_password

Added commands for the following keys: auth_protocol, auth_port

Change-Id: I3f81e4055f50c32f9ccd941e2ae2d3e6fba25a19
Closes-Bug: #1261927

commit_message:
Preserve testr temp files

If testr is killed before it finishes running, it saves its output in a
temp file.  If something times out this file may provide insight into
what was making it slow, so preserve the temp file.

Related-Bug: #1258682

Change-Id: I5cd1bc2326998bf3a1c29cd3773bf583f04ef3d5

commit_message:
Changing oozie libs setup to manual copy

Bug #1240511 consists of two connected problems:
1. oozie-setup.sh exists with status code 0 when error occurs.
2. Savanna expects that HDFS is running immediately
   after "/usr/sbin/hadoop-daemon.sh start datanode" execution

This patch addresses the first issue.
The second issue is addressed by https://review.openstack.org/62966

Temporarily changing oozie lib setup to manual copy.
Will return back when bug #1262023 is resolved.

Partially fixes bug #1240511
Change-Id: Ie4e9e2f09c2cfc5a6c79769bfc963940c6bc16c1

[{'created': '2013-12-06 04:24:05.000000000', 'message': 'Make ssync_receiver drop conn on exc

Before, the ssync receiver wouldn't hang up the connection with all
errors. Now it will. Hanging up early will ensure the remote end gets
a "broken pipe" type error right away instead of it possible sending
more data for quite some time before finally reading the error.

Change-Id: I2d3d55baaf10f99e7edce7843a7106875752020a
'}]
commit_message:
Make ssync_receiver drop conn on exc

Before, the ssync receiver wouldn't hang up the connection with all
errors. Now it will. Hanging up early will ensure the remote end gets
a "broken pipe" type error right away instead of it possible sending
more data for quite some time before finally reading the error.

Change-Id: I2d3d55baaf10f99e7edce7843a7106875752020a

commit_message:
Paginate backup list api

* Order list by updated at to show latest first
* Add pagination support for backup list and instance backup
  list
* Add tests for pagination and ordering

Implements: blueprint paginate-backup-list

Change-Id: Ie98bd2bc0500dfe4bbe0bb8b420ad80ad7f5a5df

commit_message:
Make wsgi attributes overridable

Allow the site operator to override wsgi attributes
in Grizzly sites that are patched with the following
patch:

https://gist.github.com/alanmeadows/7770570

Change-Id: I6495c9f6095e686d9504ad8dde59c9b9696dc3ba

commit_message:
Simplify update_with_template() method

self.nested() was tested against None at 2 different places in the
method. It is now tested once and if it is None, the method fails
early.

Change-Id: I1296003b359b463126536f3e45c09bd2f22aa18b

commit_message:
Replace inheritance hierarchy with composition

In the process of unification of the clients code we should use
composition to allow easier replacement with common HTTPClient.

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2

Change-Id: I5addc38eb2e2dd0be91b566fda7c0d81787ffa75

commit_message:
Tox fails to build environment because of MySQL-Python version

  During tox building environment, it try to install the package
MySQL-python version 1.2.4 but the build failed with the error:

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<string>", line 16, in <module>
  File "/opt/stack/nova/.tox/py27/build/MySQL-python/setup.py", line 18, in <module>
    metadata, options = get_config()
  File "setup_posix.py", line 43, in get_config
    libs = mysql_config("libs_r")
  File "setup_posix.py", line 25, in mysql_config
    raise EnvironmentError("%s not found" % (mysql_config.path,))
EnvironmentError: mysql_config not found

  This patch fix the version at 1.2.3

Closes-Bug: #1260667
Change-Id: I90e38094b53dc725e8c197a9f8c8419c4b01c946

commit_message:
Add volume extensions tests

This commit adds clients for the cinder extensions api and adds
tests to list the extensions, which parallels the existing tests we
have for the nova equivalent api.

Change-Id: Ie24609ade3a4884b42f75ba6f3d3d969aca37505
